        <text>
            <body>
                <lg n="1" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="1" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Ty<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ger! ty<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ger! burn<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ing <rhyme label="a">bright</rhyme></seg>
                        <note anchored="true">
                            This line, and the majority of those that follow it, exemplifies a metrical ambiguity that comes with the territory of folk poetry in English.  Seven syllables of militantly alternating stress and slack add up without question to tetrameter.  But are the feet iambs or trochees?  Or in other (Glossary-defined) words, while the line is obviously catalectic, is it an acephalous line or a case of terminal truncation?  4B4V reflects a prosodic consensus (not unanimity!) in favoring iambic scansion for such a line, on the principle that meters in English verse tend to rising (stress-ended) feet.  Join this consensus and by the time you reach line 4 you'll be glad you did.
                        </note>
                    </l>
                    <l n="2" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>In </seg>
                        <seg>the for<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ests of </seg>
                        <seg>the <rhyme label="a">night,</rhyme></seg>
                        <note anchored="true">
                            This line, and the several others like it that draw stress on initial prepositions or conjunctions that would ordinarily go slack, is a lot easier to scan once you have read the whole poem out, and out loud, and thereby have been affected, maybe infected, by its obsessiveness.  The drum-thumping chant of the increasingly frenzied speaker overrides pronunciational business as usual
                        </note>
                    </l>
                    <l n="3" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>im<sb/>mor<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>tal hand </seg>
                        <seg>or <rhyme label="b">eye</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="4" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Could frame </seg>
                        <seg>thy fear<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ful sym<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>me<sb/><rhyme label="b">try?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
                <lg n="2" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="5" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>In </seg>
                        <seg>what dis<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>tant deeps </seg>
                        <seg>or <rhyme label="a">skies</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="6" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Burnt </seg>
                        <seg>the fi<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>re of </seg>
                        <seg>thine <rhyme label="a">eyes?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="7" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-++--+-">
                        <seg>On </seg>
                        <seg>what wings </seg>
                        <seg>dare he </seg>
                        <seg>a<sb/>spi<sb/><rhyme label="b">re?</rhyme></seg>
                        <note anchored="true">
                            This line and the next may prompt you to resign from the rising-foot consensus urged in the note to line 1.  But, before quitting, consider the likelihood that in Blake's English "aspire" was a disyllable, "fire" a monosyllable.  In any case stanza 3, we predict, will send you back from trochaism into the iambic fold.
                        </note>
                    </l>
                    <l n="8" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+++-+-">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>the hand </seg>
                        <seg>dare seize </seg>
                        <seg>the fi<sb/><rhyme label="b">re?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
                <lg n="3" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="9" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+++--++">
                        <seg>And </seg>
                        <seg>what should<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>er, &amp; </seg>
                        <seg>what <rhyme label="a">art,</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="10" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Could twist </seg>
                        <seg>the sin<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ews of </seg>
                        <seg>thy <rhyme label="a">heart?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="11" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>And when </seg>
                        <seg>thy heart </seg>
                        <seg>be<sb/>gan </seg>
                        <seg>to <rhyme label="b">beat,</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="12" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+++-+++">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>dread hand? </seg>
                        <caesura/>
                        <seg>&amp; what </seg>
                        <seg>dread <rhyme label="b">feet?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
                <lg n="4" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="13" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>the ham<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>mer? <caesura/>what </seg>
                        <seg>the <rhyme label="a">chain?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="14" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+++-+-+">
                        <seg>In </seg>
                        <seg>what fur<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>nace was </seg>
                        <seg>thy <rhyme label="a">brain?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="15" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+++">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>the an<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>vil? <caesura/>what </seg>
                        <seg>dread <rhyme label="b">grasp</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="16" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Dare </seg>
                        <seg>its dead<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ly ter<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>rors <rhyme label="b">clasp?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
                <lg n="5" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="17" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+++-+">
                        <seg>When </seg>
                        <seg>the stars </seg>
                        <seg>threw down </seg>
                        <seg>their <rhyme label="a">spears,</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="18" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>And wa<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>tered heav<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>en with </seg>
                        <seg>their <rhyme label="a">tears,</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="19" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Did </seg>
                        <seg>he smile </seg>
                        <seg>his work </seg>
                        <seg>to <rhyme label="b">see?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="20" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Did he </seg>
                        <seg>who made </seg>
                        <seg>the Lamb </seg>
                        <seg>make <rhyme label="b">thee?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
                <lg n="6" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/4/4/4)" rhyme="aabb" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="21" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Ty<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ger! ty<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ger! burn<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ing <rhyme label="a">bright</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="22" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>In </seg>
                        <seg>the for<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ests of </seg>
                        <seg>the <rhyme label="a">night,</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="23" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+-+">
                        <seg>What </seg>
                        <seg>im<sb/>mor<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>tal hand </seg>
                        <seg>or <rhyme label="b">eye</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                    <l n="24" met="-+-+-+-+" real="++-+-+-+">
                        <seg>Dare frame </seg>
                        <seg>thy fear<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>ful sym<sb/></seg>
                        <seg>me<sb/><rhyme label="b">try?</rhyme></seg>
                    </l>
                </lg>
